<h2>Climate indicators for November 2017</h2>
<br><br>
The last autumn month of 2017 showed some early indications of wintertime ahead. The first frost days (where night temperatures drop below 0&#176;C) have occurred in large parts of Europe. As Figure 1 shows, the number of frost days for autumn 2017 was below the 1981-2010 climatology for most of Europe, while parts of Spain, France and the Alpine region saw areas where more frost days than usual have been observed.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2017/Stateofclimate_FD_SON_2017_anomaly_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_frost_days_index_per_time_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-11-30T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/Stateofclimate_FD_SON_2017_anomaly_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_frost_days_index_per_time_period_baselayers_overlay_2017-11-30T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Number of frost days in autumn 2017 as a deviation from the 1981-2010 autumn climatic mean.</em>
<br><br>
The anomalously low value of the number of frost days in autumn 2017 for large parts of Europe is in line with a gradually decreasing trend of this index in the past two decades. Figure 2 (lower panel) shows the number of frost days, averaged over an area in central Europe roughly overlapping with the Czech Republic and parts of neighbouring countries (between 9&#176;-18&#176;E, 48&#176;-54&#176;N). From the mid-1990s a decrease in the number of autumn frost days sets in. The autumn 2017 value is in the top-three of autumns with the lowest amount of frost days (since 1950). The first frost day for this region is around yearday 290 (~mid-Oct) but it lacks the trend observed in the number of frost days (Figure 2, upper panel), although the first frost of autumn 2017 is later than usual.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2017/forst_days_and_dates_CentralEurope.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/forst_days_and_dates_CentralEurope.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Yearday of the first frost (upper graph) and the number of frost days in autumn (lower graph), both based on E-OBS.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>The weather in November 2017</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
A marked east-west split was apparent in surface temperature across Europe during November.
Temperatures were cooler than average across western and southwestern regions, but warmer conditions than normal were experienced across eastern Europe. On most days a ridge of high pressure was located from the Atlantic Ocean into France/Spain and central Europe. The polar jet stream was shifted a bit to the north and was mainly active from the northern UK into Scandinavia. Under the ridge of high pressure calm and good radiating conditions (cloud-free conditions) occurred whereby on many nights it became colder than normal. During the last week of the month a strong northerly flow pushed into the Alps. In the upper air regions of the troposphere a belt of cold air moved into central and even southern Europe. Due to intense orographic lifting along the northern side of the Alps a lot of snow was produced especially along the leewind parts of the mountains (Figure 3).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2017/analyse_2017112812.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/analyse_2017112812.png" width="350px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: Analysis of the synoptic situation for 28 November 2017 (12:00h UTC) illustrating the orographic lifting that led to the heavy snow fall on this day in the Alpine region.</em>
<br><br>
The east-west split in temperatures is most pronounced for minimum daily temperatures, which are generally indicative of night-time temperatures.
<br><br>
