<h3>Snow cover</h3>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_mean_2017_11.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_mean_2017_11.jpg" width="175px"></a>
<a href="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_maxi_2017_11.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_maxi_2017_11.jpg" width="175px"></a>
<a href="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_days_2017_11.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2017/rcc_eude_eur_sno_days_2017_11.jpg" width="175px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 12: Mean snow depth (Left), maximum snow depth (Middle), and number of snow days (Right) in November, 2017.</em>
<br><br>
In northern and also in southern Europe the numbers of days with snow cover were above the long term mean. Southern Europe had some snow while normally there is no snow. Scandinavia and northern Russia had mostly every day measurable snow cover while in the long term mean several days were without snow. In Sweden, station Jokkmokk in the north registered the largest snow depth (60 cm).
From eastern Germany up to the Baltic States and eastern Russia the numbers of days with snow cover were below the long term mean due to above normal temperatures. In northern and central Lithuania snow cover on the last day of the month was 4 cm thick, formed on the first days and in the second half of the month.
At the end of November the snow in Austria reached the lowland with a snow depth of several centimetres. At higher elevations snow conditions in the Austrian Alps were since a long time again normal or even above normal with more than 50 cm. At the northern side of the Swiss Alps snow fell down to the lowland and at some winter sports resorts skiing was possible. At elevations of more than 700 m the maximum snow depth was 10 to 20 cm.
In several other regions of Europe snow occurred, at the Balkans more than usual and in Turkey as well as the Carpathian mountains less than normal.
<br><br>
<h3>Cloudiness and Radiation</h3>
Cloud cover over Europe has been below normal for the western and southern part of the continent.
Central and east Europe have been cloudier than usual (Figure 13). This is also reflected in the amount of radiation, showing that central and eastern Europe have seen dull conditions for most of November 2017, while Scandinavia, the UK and expecially the Iberian peninsula have been sunnier than usual.
